<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920224-0047</DOCNO><DOCID>920224-0047.</DOCID><HL>   Payless Cashways Sale   Of Up to $500 Million   Of Stock Is Planned</HL><DATE>02/24/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16</SO><CO>   X.PCI</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)SPECIALTY RETAILERS OF LIMITED PRODUCT LINES (OTS)STOCK AND BOND REGISTRATIONS, PRICINGS (REG)ALL SPECIALTY RETAILERS (RTS)STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)</IN><NS>BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, REPURCHASES, SWAPS (BBK)FINANCING AGREEMENTS (FNC)BOND AND STOCK REGISTRATIONS AND PRICINGS (REG)STOCK andamp; OTHER MARKET NEWS (STK)</NS><LP>   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Payless Cashways Inc. said it plans toreturn to the public marketplace with a common stock offeringvalued at as much as $500 million.   A management-led group took the building-materialsretailer private in 1988 through a tender offer for $27 ashare, or about $908 million.</LP><TEXT>   A Payless spokeswoman said the company decided to gopublic again because the stock market is strong and becausethe drop in interest rates has made financing such a movemore affordable.   The company is also encouraged by strong sales in itsstores, she said. January same-store sales rose about 17%,compared with a year earlier, she said. Samestore salesrefers to sales at stores that had been open at least a year.   Payless said it has applied to relist its common on theNew York Stock Exchange.   As part of the plan, Payless announced a tender offer forits $332.5 million outstanding of 14.5% senior subordinateddebentures due Nov. 1, 2000. The company said it is alsoplanning to repurchase through privately negotiatedtransactions its 16.5% junior subordinated discountdebentures due Aug. 1, 2008.   To raise funds for the moves, Payless said it plans toissue as much as $200 million in senior subordinated notesand to arrange a financing pact for as much as $450 millionwith a group of banks led by Canadian Imperial Bank ofCommerce.   Payless said it plans a public offering of $435 million to$500 million of common. The company said it filed aregistration statement with the Securities and ExchangeCommission for an offer of as many as 33.5 million shares, ofwhich 27 million would be offered in the U.S. and the restinternationally.   Payless said it is proposing an initial offering price of$13 to $15 a share. It said the public offering will bemanaged by Merrill Lynch andamp; Co., Goldman, Sachs andamp; Co. andPiper, Jaffray andamp; Hopwood Inc.   Payless operates 195 building-materials stores in 26states.</TEXT></DOC>